[reasoning process] To find what number is \(5\%\) of \(10\%\) of 1200, we first need to calculate \(10\%\) of 1200. \(10\%\) can be calculated by multiplying 1200 by \(0.10\). 

So, 
\[
10\% \text{ of } 1200 = 1200 \times 0.10 = 120
\]

Next, we need to calculate \(5\%\) of the result we just found, which is 120. We do this by multiplying 120 by \(0.05\):

\[
5\% \text{ of } 120 = 120 \times 0.05 = 6
\]

Now we have completed the calculations. 

[Verification] To verify, we will recalculate both steps. First, for \(10\%\) of 1200:
\[
10\% \text{ of } 1200 = 1200 \times 0.10 = 120
\]
This part checks out. Next, for \(5\%\) of 120:
\[
5\% \text{ of } 120 = 120 \times 0.05 = 6
\]
This also checks out. Hence, our calculations were correct.

[Final Answer] The answer is 6 \n#### 6
